                               3.0 INSTALLATION

         3.1 To  install  LTGOLD  you  must  use  the  INSTALL program
             supplied on your distribution diskette.  The files on the
             distribution  diskette are archived and must be extracted
             in the correct sequence.


      ┌─────────────────────── <-> WARNING <-> ─────────────────────────┐
      │  The program will not operate correctly if the files are not    │
      │  installed by using the supplied INSTALL program!               │
      └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘





                                    - 5 -
                                  README.ENG



         3.2 To  start  the installation process,  change your current
             drive to the one that has the installation program on  it
             and type INSTALL. For example, if you are installing from
             drive A:, type:

              A:INSTALL
                       └── Press Enter

             and follow the installation prompts from the program.

                    4.0 FEATURES AND IMPORTANT INFORMATION

         4.1 To increase the speed of LTGOLD you may use the available
             utilities  in  MS-DOS for disk cacheing. By including the
             DOS driver SMARTDRV.SYS into your  CONFIG.SYS  files  you
             can increase your speed of LTGOLD by more than 200%.  The
             following is an example of an addition to your CONFIG.SYS
             file:

              DEVICE=C:\DOS\SMARTDRV.SYS 320


         4.2 You  should  also have FILES and BUFFERS set large enough
             for the program.  The following is an example of how your
             CONFIG.SYS should look:

             (minimum required)

             BUFFERS=20
             FILES=30

         4.3 In  order  to  execute LTGOLD from any directory you must
             add an additional parameter to your drive PATH  which  is
             usually defined in the AUTOEXEC.BAT.  The following is an
             example of how your PATH should look:

              PATH C:;C:\DOS;C:\LTGOLD;

             (Please read your MS-DOS manual for  further  details  on
                the PATH command.)

         4.4 If your system has sufficient memory,  you may  define  a
             virtual disk (memory which acts like a disk drive) before
             calling the program using the MS-DOS driver RAMDRIVE.SYS.
             You  will  then  be  able  to put the LTGOLD dictionaries
             there for greater speed.  You  would  execute  LTGOLD  by
             adding the   following  parameter  -D  <V:>,  for example
             for the E: disk type:

         DEVICE=C:\DOC\HIMEM.SYS
                            └ installs the DOS high memory driver

         DEVICE=C:\DOS\RAMDRIVE.SYS 2048 /E
                                     │    └ Creates drive "E:" from the
                                     │      extended memory
                                     │
                                     └─ amount of free memory


                                    - 6 -
                                  README.ENG


      ┌───────────────────────────  NOTE ───────────────────────────────┐
      │The  two  above examples  assume  that  the files "HIMEM.SYS" and│
      │"RAMDRIVE.SYS" are located on drive C: in the Subdirectory "DOS".│
      └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘


             You may now copy the *.DIC and *.RUS files to drive E:.
             The command to start LTGOLD should read:

                  ┌────── Changes your default subdirectory to LTGOLD
          CD\LTGOLD
          LTGOLD -D E:
                  └────── Tells the program your dictionaries  are on
                           your E: drive

             and the  dictionaries  files  will  be  loaded  from  the
             virtual disk E:


         4.5 MS-DOS does not remove files from the  disk  even  though
             they  have  been  deleted.  This  feature  allows for the
             recovery of files that are accidentally deleted.  It also
             creates  a  problem  for  the  speed  of  your  system by
             fragmenting the drive (putting small fragments of  a  new
             file  in any available open space).  One program may have
             several fragments on your  hard  drive.  This  slows  the
             system down greatly. It is a very good idea to run one of
             the commercially  available  disk  compression  programs.
             Either  Mace  or  Norton  Speed  Disk   will  speed  your
             programs up.


      ┌─────────────────────── <-> WARNING <-> ─────────────────────────┐
      │ Always back your hard drive up prior to running any compression │
      │ program.                                                        │
      └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
















